      <h2>Dialectical Behavior Therapy</h2><hr>
        <p>In the United States, some 20 million women and 10 million men suffer from a clinically significant <a href="https://www.nationaleatingdisorders.org/get-facts-eating-disorders">eating disorder</a> at some time in their life, including anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, binge eating disorder.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Marsha Linehan, Ph.D. first developed dialectical behavior therapy, or DBT, in the early 1990s to treat people with severe depression. The therapy has become a centerpiece of treatment for eating disorder patients. While many are taught DBT skills by their therapists and at inpatient and outpatient treatment centers, for those who want to continue to practice on their own they are referred to the paper workbook <a href="https://www.newharbinger.com/dialectical-behavior-therapy-skills-workbook-bulimia">The Dialectical Behavior Therapy Skills Workbook</a>. This tool is an excellent resource for patients in recovery but can be cumbersome and out of reach when a patient really needs it.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The goal of <em>Within Reach</em> is to break down this barrier and put the hard work of recovery in a patient's hand - within reach at all times.</p>
